              <h6><a name="restoration_potential">RESTORATION POTENTIAL</a></h6>
              <p>This is a 1 km2 resolution dataset, showing wider landscapes where forest restoration opportunities are more likely to be found (rather than the location of potential restoration sites). The results are globally consistent, but pertain only to lands deemed capable of supporting forests or woodlands. Some areas of dry and very sparse forest fall outside of these lands but still provide significant needs and opportunities for restoration. The restoration potential of degraded and deforested land has been estimated depending on how densely the land is populated, its degree of urbanization or industrialisation, and on whether it is cropland or not Areas with high population density, or occupied by intensively managed croplands, were considered as having low/no restoration opportunities, while areas with scattered cropland areas, pastures, agroforestry and all types of forest plantations were considered as providing promising opportunities for restoration. The dataset differentiates between:</p>	
						<p><b>Promising opportunities:</b></p>
						<ul>
							<li><p>Remote restoration: Less than one person per km2 within a 500km radius. These areas could be difficult to restore due to their remoteness.</p></li>
							<li><p>Wide-scale restoration: Less than 10 people per km2 and potential to support closed forest.</p></li>
						<li><p>Mosaic restoration: Between 10 and 100 people per km2, in a mosaic landscape with several functions.</p></li>
						</ul>
<p><b>Little / no restoration opportunities:</b></p>
<ul>
	<li><p>Agricultural restoration: Croplands or densely populated rural areas on former forest lands, with over 100 people per km2. They do not offer extensive restoration opportunities in terms of area, but some of these lands would benefit from having trees planted in strategic places to protect and enhance agricultural productivity and other ecosystem functions.</p></li>
</ul>
							
